    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here is an example of how that \"hidden trap\" might play out in a real dispute:\n\nImagine your client, a tech startup, accidentally uploads a file to the wrong server. A third-party vendor's firewall then blocks that file, causing a minor data glitch. The client's CEO gets angry, reads the NDA, and immediately sues you, claiming the \"data glitch\" was a \"loss\" caused by your \"negligence\" because you didn't double-check the upload.\n\nBecause the clause says \"all losses\" and \"any and all,\" the client's lawyers can argue that the entire lawsuit, the settlement, the penalties, and even the cost of their own legal fees are all recoverable from you. They might even try to sue you for the loss of their reputation or the stock price drop, which are intangible \"losses\" that are incredibly hard to prove but easy to claim under broad language.\n\nThe \"hidden\" part is that the contract doesn't explicitly say \"we will sue you for stock price drops,\" but the broad wording allows them to do so. It's like a goblin hiding in a pile of leaves; you don't see the goblin until it jumps out and bites you",
